        {
            "id": "0274d6a23cc94eb5b4e0a",
            "questionText": "A researcher is studying a semiconductor material and wants to understand the behavior of electrons within the material's atoms, based on Rutherford's and Bohr's models. Suppose an electron in an atom within the semiconductor is orbiting the nucleus with a velocity $!$v = 2.19 \\times 10^6 \\text{ m/s}$!$ in the $!$n = 1$!$ orbit. Using the principles of angular momentum quantization, calculate the radius of this orbit in terms of Bohr radius $!$a = \\frac{h^2}{4\\pi^2 k e^2 m}$!$, given that the mass of the electron is $!$9.11 \\times 10^{-31} \\text{ kg}$!$ and Planck's constant is $!$h = 6.626 \\times 10^{-34} \\text{ J s}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "37c2aa62f5494abf8c1f8",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula for angular momentum quantization of an electron in orbit. Which of the following expressions represents the quantization condition?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "933e7925-8098-434d-a7e9-8b87f134afa3",
                        "f3adea61-e184-4afc-af61-87a032de7132"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$mvr = n\\frac{h}{2\\pi}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$mv^2 = n\\frac{h}{2\\pi}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{h}{mv}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$mvr = h$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "d8fa1fe18c5f47eebfe4a",
                    "stepText": "Great. Now, using that quantization relation for the case $!$n=1$!$, rearrange the formula to isolate the orbital radius $!$r$!$. Which of the following expressions correctly isolates $!$r$!$ in terms of $!$h$!$, $!$m$!$, and $!$v$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "933e7925-8098-434d-a7e9-8b87f134afa3"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{h}{2\\pi mv}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{2\\pi mv}{h}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{mv}{2\\pi h}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{h}{mv}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "8a43b746441e4937aefb3",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have the correct expression, substitute the values $!$h = 6.626\\times10^{-34}\\text{ J s}$!$, $!$m = 9.11\\times10^{-31}\\text{ kg}$!$, and $!$v = 2.19\\times10^6 \\text{ m/s}$!$ into $!$r = \\frac{h}{2\\pi m v}$!$ and compute the orbit radius. What is the numerical value you obtain for $!$r$!$?",
